IllustratedAmerican1892 and document group.  Might need to coordinate with Rachel and Eric E. on this!}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2914953 
 than by its geographical name, and while the peculiar features of the semi-desert bit of land have appealed to popular fancy little attenti
on has been given to either the marooned woman or the reason why she was there. In fact, her very presence and rescue are almost looked upon as myths by the later residents who have gradually taken the places of the first population of Ventura and Santa B
arbara counties.
\par 
\par San C[l]emente's shores are bleak and drear, guarded by inhospitable coasts, where rock and wave of restless ocean serve to keep off all except those who are driven by necessity or curiousity to visit the land. High cliffs, running up thou
sands of feet above the water, seem to guard the secrets of the island, and there is nothing inviting in the appearance or the prospects of the land.{\*\atrfstart 441950229}
 For this reason all early navigators passed the island by, and thus it came about that the lone Indian wom
an finally ceased to hope for rescue, and, with the stolidity of her race, abandoned herself to her fate, thinking, if she ever thought at all, that she would end her days near where her baby had perished at the time she was left to live or die as fate wi
lled.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af31507\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid3605128 {\*\atrfend 441950229}{\*\atnid SS}{\*\atnauthor Sara Schwebel}\chatn {\*\annotation{\*\atnref 441950229}{\*\atndate -2025738760}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar
